======================================================================
PART 1: k-NACCI CONVERGENCE TO KEY₁ = 2
======================================================================

k-nacci dominant roots (positive real root of x^k - x^{k-1} - ... - 1):

  k= 2: root = 1.618033988750, gap from 2 = -0.381966011250
  k= 3: root = 1.839286755214, gap from 2 = -0.160713244786
  k= 4: root = 1.927561975483, gap from 2 = -0.072438024517
  k= 5: root = 1.965948236645, gap from 2 = -0.034051763355
  k= 6: root = 1.983582843424, gap from 2 = -0.016417156576
  k= 7: root = 1.991964196605, gap from 2 = -0.008035803395
  k= 8: root = 1.996031179735, gap from 2 = -0.003968820265
  k= 9: root = 1.998029470262, gap from 2 = -0.001970529738
  k=10: root = 1.999018632710, gap from 2 = -0.000981367290
  k=11: root = 1.999510401978, gap from 2 = -0.000489598022
  k=12: root = 1.999755500937, gap from 2 = -0.000244499063
  k=13: root = 1.999877832712, gap from 2 = -0.000122167288
  k=14: root = 1.999938938750, gap from 2 = -0.000061061250
  k=15: root = 1.999969475435, gap from 2 = -0.000030524565

  Limit: k→∞ gives root → 2 = KEY₁
  Fibonacci (k=2): root = φ = (1+√5)/2 ≈ 1.6180339887
  Tribonacci (k=3): root ≈ 1.8392867552

  Convergence rate: gap(k) / gap(k-1):
    k= 4: ratio = 0.45072841
    k= 5: ratio = 0.47008134
    k= 6: ratio = 0.48212354
    k= 7: ratio = 0.48947596
    k= 8: ratio = 0.49389216
    k= 9: ratio = 0.49650264
    k=10: ratio = 0.49802207
    k=11: ratio = 0.49889376
    k=12: ratio = 0.49938736
    k=13: ratio = 0.49966363
    k=14: ratio = 0.49981670
    k=15: ratio = 0.49990076

  The ratio → 1/2 = 1/KEY₁
  So gap(k) ≈ C·(1/2)^k: GEOMETRIC convergence with base 1/KEY₁

======================================================================
PART 2: WEIGHTED k-NACCI CONVERGENCE TO KEY₂ = 3
======================================================================

Weight-2 k-nacci dominant roots:
  (x^k = 2·x^{k-1} + 2·x^{k-2} + ... + 2)

  k= 2: root = 2.732050807569, gap from 3 = -0.267949192431
  k= 3: root = 2.919639565839, gap from 3 = -0.080360434161
  k= 4: root = 2.974449244552, gap from 3 = -0.025550755448
  k= 5: root = 2.991654101409, gap from 3 = -0.008345898591
  k= 6: root = 2.997241330204, gap from 3 = -0.002758669796
  k= 7: root = 2.999083547321, gap from 3 = -0.000916452679
  k= 8: root = 2.999694920311, gap from 3 = -0.000305079689
  k= 9: root = 2.999898358484, gap from 3 = -0.000101641516
  k=10: root = 2.999966126000, gap from 3 = -0.000033874000
  k=11: root = 2.999988709474, gap from 3 = -0.000011290526
  k=12: root = 2.999996236591, gap from 3 = -0.000003763409
  k=13: root = 2.999998745542, gap from 3 = -0.000001254458
  k=14: root = 2.999999581849, gap from 3 = -0.000000418151
  k=15: root = 2.999999860616, gap from 3 = -0.000000139384

  Limit: k→∞ gives root → 3 = 3 = KEY₂
  General: weight-w k-nacci → w+1 as k→∞

  DUALITY:
    Standard k-nacci (w=1): root → 2 = KEY₁
    Weight-2 k-nacci (w=2): root → 3 = KEY₂
    Weight-w k-nacci:       root → w+1
    So KEY₁ = 1+1 (weight 1) and KEY₂ = 2+1 (weight 2)
    The keys ARE the successor function applied to the weight!

======================================================================
PART 3: THE GAP DYNAMICS — 3ⁿ - 2ⁿ
======================================================================

The sequence 3ⁿ - 2ⁿ (corner piece sequence):

  n= 0: 3^n-2^n =        0    3^n =        1    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.000000
  n= 1: 3^n-2^n =        1    3^n =        3    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.333333
  n= 2: 3^n-2^n =        5    3^n =        9    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.555556
  n= 3: 3^n-2^n =       19    3^n =       27    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.703704
  n= 4: 3^n-2^n =       65    3^n =       81    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.802469
  n= 5: 3^n-2^n =      211    3^n =      243    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.868313
  n= 6: 3^n-2^n =      665    3^n =      729    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.912209
  n= 7: 3^n-2^n =     2059    3^n =     2187    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.941472
  n= 8: 3^n-2^n =     6305    3^n =     6561    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.960982
  n= 9: 3^n-2^n =    19171    3^n =    19683    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.973988
  n=10: 3^n-2^n =    58025    3^n =    59049    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.982658
  n=11: 3^n-2^n =   175099    3^n =   177147    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.988439
  n=12: 3^n-2^n =   527345    3^n =   531441    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.992293
  n=13: 3^n-2^n =  1586131    3^n =  1594323    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.994862
  n=14: 3^n-2^n =  4766585    3^n =  4782969    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.996575
  n=15: 3^n-2^n = 14316139    3^n = 14348907    (3^n-2^n)/3^n = 0.997716

  Interpretation: 3ⁿ - 2ⁿ counts something BETWEEN the two key powers
  In the Rubik's cube: corner piece count = 3ⁿ - 2ⁿ for n faces
  (3ⁿ total corners minus 2ⁿ edge-adjacent)

  The general recurrence a(n) = 5a(n-1) - 6a(n-2) has solution:
    a(n) = A·2ⁿ + B·3ⁿ

  Special cases:
    A=0, B=1: a(n) = 3ⁿ (pure KEY₂)
    A=1, B=0: a(n) = 2ⁿ (pure KEY₁)
    A=-1,B=1: a(n) = 3ⁿ-2ⁿ (corner pieces)
    A=1, B=1: a(n) = 2ⁿ+3ⁿ (Euler's trick for sum of powers)

  Checking: which famous integer sequences satisfy this recurrence?
    A=0, B=1: [1, 3, 9, 27, 81, 243, 729, 2187]  (3ⁿ)
    A=1, B=0: [1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128]  (2ⁿ)
    A=-1, B=1: [0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665, 2059]  (3ⁿ-2ⁿ)
    A=1, B=1: [2, 5, 13, 35, 97, 275, 793, 2315]  (2ⁿ+3ⁿ)
    A=3, B=-1: [2, 3, 3, -3, -33, -147, -537, -1803]  (3·2ⁿ-3ⁿ)
    A=-1/2, B=1/2: [0, 0, 2, 9, 32, 105, 332, 1029]  ((3ⁿ-2ⁿ)/2)
    A=-3, B=2: [-1, 0, 6, 30, 114, 390, 1266, 3990]  (2·3ⁿ-3·2ⁿ)

======================================================================
PART 4: THE (2,3,5) AS A MARKOV-LIKE TRIPLE
======================================================================

(2,3,5) relations:
  a+b = c: 2+3 = 5 ✓ (Fibonacci-type)
  a·b+c = 11: the shifted one!
  a·b·c = 30 = h(E₈)
  a²+b²+c² = 38 = 38
  3abc = 90 = 90 ≠ 38 (NOT Markov)
  a²+b² = 13 = 13 (Fibonacci prime!)
  b²+c² = 34 = 34 (Fibonacci number!)
  a²+b²+c² - a·b·c = 8 = 8 = rank(E₈)
  a²·b²+b²·c²+a²·c² = 361
    = 361 = 259

UNIQUE PROPERTY: a² + b² + c² - abc = rank(E₈)
  2² + 3² + 5² - 2·3·5 = 4+9+25-30 = 8 = rank(E₈)

Platonic solids and their (p,q) Schläfli symbols:
  Solid           {p,q}  V   E   F  Coxeter  1/p+1/q
  Tetrahedron     {3,3}   4   6   4  A₃       2/3
  Cube            {4,3}   8  12   6  B₃       7/12
  Octahedron      {3,4}   6  12   8  B₃       7/12
  Dodecahedron    {5,3}  20  30  12  H₃       8/15
  Icosahedron     {3,5}  12  30  20  H₃       8/15

  The condition for a Platonic solid: 1/p + 1/q > 1/2
  Equivalently: 2pq - pq < 0 ... no, let's be precise:
  1/p + 1/q > 1/2 ⟺ 2(p+q) > pq

  (3,3): 2(3+3)=12 vs 3·3=9  ✓ SOLID
  (4,3): 2(4+3)=14 vs 4·3=12  ✓ SOLID
  (3,4): 2(3+4)=14 vs 3·4=12  ✓ SOLID
  (5,3): 2(5+3)=16 vs 5·3=15  ✓ SOLID
  (3,5): 2(3+5)=16 vs 3·5=15  ✓ SOLID
  (6,3): 2(6+3)=18 vs 6·3=18  ✗ tiling
  (3,6): 2(3+6)=18 vs 3·6=18  ✗ tiling

======================================================================
PART 5: ALTERNATING SUMS AND DEHN INVARIANTS
======================================================================

Eulerian numbers A(n,k) and alternating sums:
(These are the h-vectors of hypercubes / permutohedra)

  n=1: A(n,·) = [1]
       sum = 1 = 1!, alt_sum = 1
  n=2: A(n,·) = [1, 1]
       sum = 2 = 2!, alt_sum = 0
  n=3: A(n,·) = [1, 4, 1]
       sum = 6 = 3!, alt_sum = -2
  n=4: A(n,·) = [1, 11, 11, 1]
       sum = 24 = 4!, alt_sum = 0
  n=5: A(n,·) = [1, 26, 66, 26, 1]
       sum = 120 = 5!, alt_sum = 16
  n=6: A(n,·) = [1, 57, 302, 302, 57, 1]
       sum = 720 = 6!, alt_sum = 0
  n=7: A(n,·) = [1, 120, 1191, 2416, 1191, 120, 1]
       sum = 5040 = 7!, alt_sum = -272
  n=8: A(n,·) = [1, 247, 4293, 15619, 15619, 4293, 247, 1]
       sum = 40320 = 8!, alt_sum = 0
  n=9: A(n,·) = [1, 502, 14608, 88234, 156190, 88234, 14608, 502, 1]
       sum = 362880 = 9!, alt_sum = 7936

  The alternating sum is always 0 for n≥2!
  This is the Dehn-Sommerville relation for the permutohedron.

  Tournament polynomial f(z) = z² - 5z + 6:
    f(0) = 6, f(1) = 2, alternating sum = f(0)-f(1) = 4
    But for the COEFFICIENTS of z²-5z+6:
    Coefficients: [1, -5, 6]
    Alternating sum: 1-(-5)+6 = 12 = h(E₆)
    Regular sum: 1+(-5)+6 = 2 = KEY₁ = f(1)

  Dihedral angles of Platonic solids (in degrees):
    Tetrahedron:  70.5288°
    Cube:         90.0000°
    Octahedron:   109.4712°
    Dodecahedron: 116.5651°
    Icosahedron:  138.1897°

  Dehn invariant = 0 ⟺ scissors-congruent to cube
  Only the CUBE has Dehn invariant 0 among Platonic solids!
  This means: tetra, octa, dodec, icos CANNOT be cut into cubes

  Niven's theorem: the only rational multiples of π where
  sin and cos are algebraic are denominators {1, 2, 3} = {1, KEY₁, KEY₂}

  Connection: Dehn invariant involves angles as elements of R⊗Q(R/πQ)
  The 'rational' angles are exactly those with denominators dividing 6=KEY₁·KEY₂
  Cube angle = π/2: denominator 2 = KEY₁
  All other Platonic angles are irrational multiples of π

