  n=11: T(n) = 36028797018963968, n! =     39916800, T/n! = 902597327.9162
  n=12: T(n) = 73786976294838206464, n! =    479001600, T/n! = 154043277297.6921
  n=13: T(n) = 3.022315e+23, n! = 6.227021e+09, T/n! = 4.8535e+13
  n=14: T(n) = 2.475880e+27, n! = 8.717829e+10, T/n! = 2.8400e+16

  T(n)/n! = number of non-isomorphic tournaments (by Burnside, approx)

  n= 2: log₂(T) =    1, log₂(n!) =     1.00, diff =     0.00
  n= 3: log₂(T) =    3, log₂(n!) =     2.58, diff =     0.42
  n= 4: log₂(T) =    6, log₂(n!) =     4.58, diff =     1.42
  n= 5: log₂(T) =   10, log₂(n!) =     6.91, diff =     3.09
  n= 6: log₂(T) =   15, log₂(n!) =     9.49, diff =     5.51
  n= 7: log₂(T) =   21, log₂(n!) =    12.30, diff =     8.70
  n= 8: log₂(T) =   28, log₂(n!) =    15.30, diff =    12.70
  n= 9: log₂(T) =   36, log₂(n!) =    18.47, diff =    17.53
  n=10: log₂(T) =   45, log₂(n!) =    21.79, diff =    23.21 ← ZERO CROSSING
  n=11: log₂(T) =   55, log₂(n!) =    25.25, diff =    29.75
  n=12: log₂(T) =   66, log₂(n!) =    28.84, diff =    37.16
  n=13: log₂(T) =   78, log₂(n!) =    32.54, diff =    45.46
  n=14: log₂(T) =   91, log₂(n!) =    36.34, diff =    54.66

  The moat is at n=10 = 2·5 = KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂)
  = Petersen vertex count!
  The Petersen graph literally sits at the tournament-factorial boundary.

  Before n=10: factorial symmetry dominates (few non-iso tournaments)
  After n=10: binary choices dominate (exponentially many non-iso tournaments)
  The Petersen graph K(5,2) marks this phase transition!

======================================================================
PART 7: 7 = 2²+3 AND 8 = 2³ — THE FIRST COMPOSITE KEYS
======================================================================

7 = KEY₁² + KEY₂ = 4 + 3:
  7 is the smallest number NOT dividing 30 = KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)
  7 is the first E₈ exponent after 1
  7 = rank(E₇)
  f(7) = (7-2)(7-3) = 5·4 = 20 = V(dodecahedron)
  7 = h(G₂) + 1 = 6 + 1
  7 = smallest prime not in {2,3,5} = first 'free' prime for E₈
  C(7,2) = 21 = number of tournament multiples in [1,30)

8 = KEY₁³ = 2³:
  8 = rank(E₈)
  8 = φ(30) = #{totatives of 30}
  8 = τ(30) = #{divisors of 30}
  f(8) = (8-2)(8-3) = 6·5 = 30 = h(E₈)
  f(KEY₁³) = h(E₈): the polynomial at rank gives Coxeter number!
  8 = number of 3-dimensional crystallographic point groups with det=1

The 7-8 pair (KEY₁²+KEY₂, KEY₁³):
  7·8 = 56 = T(6) = dim(V_E₇) = f(10)
  7+8 = 15 = C(6,2) = E(Petersen)
  8-7 = 1 (adjacent)
  8/7 ≈ 1.142857 (close to 1, slowly diverging)
  log₂(7) = 2.807355 ≈ KEY₁+0.8074
  log₃(8) = 1.892789 ≈ KEY₁-0.1072

  E₈ exponents: {1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29}
  Gaps:          6, 4,  2,  4,  2,  4,  6
  First gap: 7-1 = 6 = h(G₂) = KEY₁·KEY₂
  The gaps are palindromic: [6,4,2,4,2,4,6]
  Gap sum: 28 = 28 = T(8) in binary = rank(E₈)·(rank(E₈)-1)/2-...
  Actually 29-1 = 28 = C(8,2) = the LAST - FIRST = range

======================================================================
PART 8: 10 AND 11 AS SHIFTED ONES
======================================================================

10 = 1 shifted left in decimal:
  10 = KEY₁ · (KEY₁+KEY₂) = 2·5
  10 = V(Petersen)
  f(10) = 56 = T(6) = dim(V_E₇)
  In every base b, 10_b = b (the shifted identity)
  In binary: 10₂ = 2 = KEY₁
  In ternary: 10₃ = 3 = KEY₂
  In base 5: 10₅ = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂
  So '10' in base b means b: it IS the base!

11 = 1 repeated:
  11 = KEY₁·KEY₂ + (KEY₁+KEY₂) = 6+5
  f(11) = 72 = σ(30) = rank(E₈)·9
  In binary: 11₂ = 3 = KEY₂
  In ternary: 11₃ = 4 = KEY₁²
  In base 5: 11₅ = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)
  In base b: 11_b = b+1 = next(b)
  So 11 in base KEY₁ gives KEY₂, and vice versa!

The 10-11 pair:
  10·11 = 110 = C(11,2) + ... hmm, 110 = 2·5·11
  10+11 = 21 = #tournament multiples of (2,3,5) in [1,30)
  f(10)·f(11) = 56·72 = 4032 = 2⁶·3²·7 = KEY₁⁶·KEY₂²·7
  f(10)+f(11) = 56+72 = 128 = 2⁷ = KEY₁^rank(E₇)

  REMARKABLE: f(10) + f(11) = 2⁷ = KEY₁^rank(E₇)
  Also: f(10) = 56 = 2³·7 and f(11) = 72 = 2³·9
  So f(10) = 8·7 and f(11) = 8·9
  f(10)+f(11) = 8·(7+9) = 8·16 = 128 = 2⁷

  In the MODULAR perspective:
    10 mod  2 = 0, 11 mod  2 = 1 ← 10≡0
    10 mod  3 = 1, 11 mod  3 = 2 ← 10≡1
    10 mod  5 = 0, 11 mod  5 = 1 ← 10≡0
    10 mod  6 = 4, 11 mod  6 = 5
    10 mod  7 = 3, 11 mod  7 = 4
    10 mod  8 = 2, 11 mod  8 = 3
    10 mod 12 = 10, 11 mod 12 = 11
    10 mod 30 = 10, 11 mod 30 = 11

  10 ≡ 1 (mod 3) and 11 ≡ 1 (mod 2, 5): shifted ones in key bases!
  10 ≡ 1 (mod 3) ≡ 1 (mod 9): shifted one in KEY₂ and KEY₂²
  11 ≡ 1 (mod 2) ≡ 1 (mod 5): shifted one in KEY₁ and KEY₁+KEY₂

======================================================================
PART 9: THE n=9 TRANSITION — FROM 2³ TO 3²
======================================================================

The landscape around n=9:

  n= 6: C(n,2)= 15, T(n)=     32768, f(n)=  12 = 2·2·3
  n= 7: C(n,2)= 21, T(n)=   2097152, f(n)=  20 = 2·2·5
  n= 8: C(n,2)= 28, T(n)= 268435456, f(n)=  30 = 2·3·5
  n= 9: C(n,2)= 36, T(n)=68719476736, f(n)=  42 = 2·3·7
  n=10: C(n,2)= 45, T(n)=35184372088832, f(n)=  56 = 2·2·2·7
  n=11: C(n,2)= 55, T(n)=36028797018963968, f(n)=  72 = 2·2·2·3·3
  n=12: C(n,2)= 66, T(n)=73786976294838206464, f(n)=  90 = 2·3·3·5

  AT n=9 (= KEY₂² = 3²):
    C(9,2) = 36 = 6² = (KEY₁·KEY₂)²
    f(9) = 42 = 2·3·7 = V(icos)+V(dodec)+V(Petersen)
    42 = 6·7 = h(G₂)·rank(E₇)
    #3-cycles in regular T₉ = 30 = h(E₈)

  THE TRANSITION 8 → 9 is 2³ → 3²:
    8 = KEY₁³: cubic power of first key
    9 = KEY₂²: square power of second key
    8·9 = 72 = f(11) = σ(30)
    8+9 = 17: fifth E₈ exponent!
    9-8 = 1: adjacent integers
    9/8 = 9/8 = the 'Pythagorean' whole tone in music

  MUSICAL INTERLUDE: the 9/8 whole tone
    In Pythagorean tuning: whole tone = 9/8 = KEY₂²/KEY₁³
    Perfect fifth = 3/2 = KEY₂/KEY₁
    Perfect fourth = 4/3 = KEY₁²/KEY₂
    Octave = 2/1 = KEY₁
    Major third = 81/64 = (KEY₂/KEY₁)⁴/KEY₁
    Pythagorean comma = 3¹²/2¹⁹ ≈ 1.013643
    The comma ≈ 1.013643 is the 'gap' between the two keys
    after 12 fifths vs 7 octaves: KEY₂¹² vs KEY₁¹⁹
    12 = h(E₆), 19 = h₊₁(E₈) ... hmm

  THE (p,q) TABLE:
         q=1    q=2    q=3
  p=2:   2      4=2²   8=2³
  p=3:   3      9=3²   27=3³
  p=5:   5     25=5²  125=5³

  The 2×3 block {2,3,4,8,9,27} contains:
    2,3 = the keys
    4 = KEY₁² = rank(F₄)
    8 = KEY₁³ = rank(E₈)
    9 = KEY₂² = CS_boundary = h∨(F₄)
    27 = KEY₂³ = dim(V_E₆)

======================================================================
PART 10: THE (2,3,5) IN STERN-BROCOT AND CONTINUED FRACTIONS
======================================================================

Golden ratio φ = (1+√5)/2 = [1; 1, 1, 1, ...]
Convergents:
  2/1 = 2.0000000000
  3/2 = 1.5000000000  ← denominator = tournament prime!
  5/3 = 1.6666666667  ← denominator = tournament prime!
  8/5 = 1.6000000000  ← denominator = tournament prime!
  13/8 = 1.6250000000
  21/13 = 1.6153846154
  34/21 = 1.6190476190
  55/34 = 1.6176470588
  89/55 = 1.6181818182

  The first three Fibonacci primes: 2, 3, 5 = the tournament triple!
  φ's convergents 'discover' the tournament primes in order.

  In the Stern-Brocot tree:
    Level 0: 1/1
    Level 1: 1/2, 2/1
    Level 2: 1/3, 2/3, 3/2, 3/1
    Level 3: 1/4, 2/5, 3/5, 3/4, 4/3, 5/3, 5/2, 4/1

    The fraction KEY₂/KEY₁ = 3/2 appears at level 2
    This is the 'simplest' ratio between the two keys
    In music: the perfect fifth (most consonant interval after octave)

  KEY₂/KEY₁ = 3/2 = [1; 2] (finite continued fraction)
  KEY₁+KEY₂ / KEY₁·KEY₂ = 5/6 = [0; 1, 5] 
  KEY₁·KEY₂ / (KEY₁+KEY₂) = 6/5 = [1; 5]
  h(E₈)/rank(E₈) = 30/8 = 15/4 = [3; 1, 3]

======================================================================
GRAND SYNTHESIS: THE DYNAMICAL PICTURE
======================================================================

The universe of (2,3,5) is a DYNAMICAL SYSTEM:

1. TWO ATTRACTORS: KEY₁=2 and KEY₂=3
   - k-nacci recurrences approach 2 from above
   - weighted k-nacci approach 3 from above
   - The gap is always exactly 1 (in the limit)

2. THE POLYNOMIAL f(z)=(z-2)(z-3) IS THE POTENTIAL:
   - Zeros at the two attractors
   - Minimum at z=5/2 with f(5/2)=-1/4
   - Integer evaluations encode the exceptional Lie data
   - Vertex at (5/2, -1/4): KEY₁+KEY₂ over KEY₁ = midpoint

3. THE SIEVE f(z) ≡ 0 mod 30 CREATES TWO WORLDS:
   - Multiples of {2,3,5}: tournament theory (21 numbers)
   - Coprime to 30: Lie exponent theory (8 numbers)
   - The two worlds are complementary: partition ALL integers

4. THE BOUNDARY AT 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂:
   - (2,3,5) is the last spherical triple
   - After 5, no more Platonic solids (hexagonal tiling is flat)
   - The Petersen K(5,2) guards this boundary
   - Its 10 vertices mark T(n) > n! crossover

5. THE RECURRENCE BACKBONE:
   - Every sequence A·2ⁿ + B·3ⁿ satisfies a(n) = 5a(n-1) - 6a(n-2)
   - 3ⁿ always wins (KEY₂ dominates)
   - But 2ⁿ controls the parity structure
   - The gap 3ⁿ-2ⁿ grows geometrically with ratio → 3

6. MUSIC, GEOMETRY, AND ALGEBRA AGREE:
   - 3/2 = perfect fifth (music)
   - (2,3,5) = spherical triple (geometry)
   - E₈ = last exceptional Lie group (algebra)
   - The Pythagorean comma ≈ 3¹²/2¹⁹ measures the mismatch
   - 12 = h(E₆), 19 = ... the Lie numbers appear naturally

ONE SENTENCE:
  The characteristic polynomial z²-5z+6 = (z-2)(z-3) generates
  the ADE classification through its sieve at 30 = 2·3·5,
  the Petersen graph as the moat guardian at 10 = 2·5,
  and all Platonic solids through the spherical condition 1/p+1/q > 1/2.
